    A Set implementation based on a modified skip list. Elements are sorted from least to greatest according to their natural ordering, or by an explicit Comparator provided at creation. Attempting to insert null elements will succeed if the Comparator supports null values. Inserting non-comparable elements will result in a ClassCastException.

    The iterators obtained from the iterator() method are fail-fast. Attempts to modify the elements in this set at any time after an iterator is created, in any way except through the iterator's own remove method, will result in a ConcurrentModificationException.

    This set is not thread-safe. If multiple threads modify this set concurrently it must be synchronized externally.

    This implementation uses a comparator (whether or not one is explicitly provided) to perform all element comparisons. Two elements which are deemed equal by the comparator's compare(E, E) method are, from the standpoint of this set, equal.

    Invented by Bill Pugh in 1990, A skip list is a probabilistic data structure for maintaining items in sorted order. Strictly speaking it is impossible to make any hard guarantees regarding the worst-case performance of this class. Practical performance is expected to be logarithmic with an extremely high degree of probability as the skip list grows.
